'''Gold''', commonly known as '''Gold Beach''', was the [[code name]] for one of the five areas of the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] invasion of [[German military administration in occupied France during World War II|German-occupied France]] in the [[Normandy landings]] on 6 June 1944, during the [[World War II|Second World War]]. Gold, the central of the five areas, was located between [[Port-en-Bessin-Huppain|Port-en-Bessin]] on the west and [[La Rivière-Saint-Sauveur|La Rivière]] on the east. High cliffs at the western end of the zone meant that the landings took place on the flat section between [[Asnelles|Le Hamel]] and La Rivière, in the sectors code-named Jig and King. Taking Gold was to be the responsibility of the [[British Army]], with sea transport, mine sweeping, and [[List of ships in Bombarding Force K|a naval bombardment force]] provided by the [[Royal Navy]] as well as elements from the [[Royal Netherlands Navy|Dutch]], [[Polish Navy|Polish]] and other Allied navies.
The objectives at Gold were to secure a [[beachhead]], move west to capture [[Arromanches]] and establish contact with the [[1st Infantry Division (United Kingdom)|American forces]] at [[Omaha Beach|Omaha]], capture [[Bayeux]] and the small port at Port-en-Bessin, and to link up with the [[3rd Canadian Division|Canadian forces]] at [[Juno Beach|Juno]] to the east. Forces attacking Gold faced elements of the [[352nd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|German 352nd Infantry Division]] and [[716th Static Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|German 716th Infantry Division]]. About 2,000 men were stationed in the immediate area. Improvements to fortifications along the Normandy coast had been undertaken under the leadership of ''[[Generalfeldmarschall]]'' [[Erwin Rommel]] beginning in October 1943.
On [[D-Day (military term)|D-Day]] at Gold, naval bombardment got underway at 05:30, and amphibious landings commenced at 07:25. High winds made conditions difficult for the landing craft, and the amphibious [[DD tank]]s were released close to shore or directly on the beach instead of further out as planned. Three of the four guns in a large emplacement at the [[Longues-sur-Mer battery]] were disabled by direct hits from the cruisers ''{{HMS|Ajax|22|2}}'' and ''{{HMS|Argonaut|61|2}}'' at 06:20. The fourth gun resumed firing intermittently in the afternoon, and its garrison surrendered on 7 June. Aerial attacks had failed to hit the Le Hamel strongpoint, which had its [[embrasure]] facing east to provide [[enfilade]] fire along the beach and had a thick concrete wall on the seaward side. Its 75&nbsp;mm gun continued to do damage until 16:00, when a modified [[Armoured Vehicle Royal Engineers]] (AVRE) tank fired a large [[Petard#Variants|Petard bomb]] into its rear entrance. A second [[casemate]]d emplacement at La Rivière containing an 88&nbsp;mm gun was neutralised by a tank at 07:30.
Meanwhile, infantry began clearing the heavily fortified houses along the shore and advanced on targets further inland. The [[British Commandos]] of [[No. 47 (Royal Marine) Commando]] advanced on Port-en-Bessin and captured it on 7 June in the [[Battle of Port-en-Bessin]]. On the western flank, the 1st Battalion, [[Royal Hampshire Regiment|Hampshire Regiment]] captured Arromanches (future site of one of the artificial [[Mulberry harbour]]s), and [[69th Infantry Brigade (United Kingdom)|69th Infantry Brigade]] on the eastern flank made contact with the Canadian forces at Juno. [[Company sergeant major|Company Sergeant Major]] [[Stanley Hollis]] received the only [[Victoria Cross]] awarded on D-Day for his actions while attacking two pillboxes at the Mont Fleury battery. Due to stiff resistance from the German 352nd Infantry Division, Bayeux was not captured until the next day. British casualties at Gold are estimated at 1,000–1,100. German casualties are unknown.
==Background==
===Operation Overlord=== {{Further|Invasion of Normandy|Operation Overlord}} [[File:Allied Invasion Force.jpg|thumb|left|Allied invasion plans and German preparations in Normandy]] After the Germans [[Operation Barbarossa|invaded the Soviet Union]] in June 1941, Soviet leader [[Joseph Stalin]] began pressing for the creation of a [[Western Front (World War II)#1944–45: the second front|second front]] in Western Europe.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|p=9}} The decision to undertake a cross-channel invasion of continental Europe within the next year was taken at the [[Trident Conference]], held in Washington in May 1943.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|p=11}} The Allies initially planned to launch the invasion on 1 May 1944, and a draft of the plan was accepted at the [[Quebec Conference, 1943|Quebec Conference]] in August 1943.{{sfn|Wilmot|1997|p=170}}{{sfn|Gilbert|1989|p=491}} General [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] was appointed commander of [[Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force]] (SHAEF).{{sfn|Gilbert|1989|p=491}} General [[Bernard Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery of Alamein|Bernard Montgomery]] was named as commander of the [[21st Army Group]], which comprised all of the land forces involved in the invasion.{{sfn|Whitmarsh|2009|pp=12–13}}
On 31 December 1943, Eisenhower and Montgomery first saw the plan, which proposed amphibious landings by three [[Division (military)|divisions]] and two-thirds of an airborne division.{{sfn|Balkoski|2005|p=5}} The two generals immediately insisted that the scale of the initial invasion be expanded to five divisions, with airborne descents by three divisions, to allow operations on a wider front.{{sfn|Whitmarsh|2009|p=13}} The change doubled the frontage of the invasion from {{convert|25|mi}} to {{convert|50|mi}}. This would allow for quicker offloading of men and [[materiel]], make it more difficult for the Germans to respond, and speed up the capture of the port at [[Cherbourg]].{{sfn|Balkoski|2005|p=10}} The need to acquire or produce extra landing craft and troop carrier aircraft for the expanded operation meant that the invasion had to be delayed to June.{{sfn|Balkoski|2005|p=19}}
The Americans, assigned to land at [[Utah Beach|Utah]] and [[Omaha Beach|Omaha]], were to cut off the [[Cotentin Peninsula]] and capture the port facilities at Cherbourg. The British at [[Sword Beach|Sword]] and Gold, and the Canadians at [[Juno Beach|Juno]], were to capture [[Caen]] and form a front line from [[Caumont-l'Éventé]] to the south-east of Caen to protect the American flank, while establishing airfields near Caen. Possession of Caen and its surroundings would provide a suitable staging area for a push south to capture the town of [[Falaise, Calvados|Falaise]]. A secure lodgement would be established and an attempt made to hold all territory north of the [[Avranches]]-Falaise line during the first three weeks. The Allied armies would then swing left to advance towards the [[River Seine]].{{sfn|Churchill|1951|pp=592–593}}{{sfn|Beevor|2009|loc=Map, inside front cover}}{{sfn|Ellis|Allen|Warhurst|2004|pp=78, 81}} Montgomery envisaged a ninety-day battle, ending when all the forces reached the Seine.{{sfn|Weinberg|1995|p=698}}
===Allied planning===
Originally, seventeen sectors along the Normandy coastline had been selected as possible invasion sites and each were provided with a code name taken from one of the [[spelling alphabet]]s of the time. The coast was divided between Able, west of Omaha, to Rodger on the eastern flank of the invasion area. Eight further sectors were added when the planned invasion was extended to include Utah. Each sector was further subdivided into beaches identified by the colours Green, Red, and White. Gold did not refer to a particular beach but to a landing area.{{sfn|Buckingham|2004|p=88}} It was delineated by [[Port-en-Bessin-Huppain|Port-en-Bessin]] on the west and La Rivière on the east, and included [[Arromanches]], location of one of the artificial [[Mulberry harbour]]s that were to be constructed shortly after the invasion. High cliffs at the western end of the zone meant that the landings would be undertaken on the flat beach between Le Hamel and La Rivière, in the sectors code-named Jig and King.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|p=276}} The area immediately behind the beach was marshy, with open ground and [[bocage]] (small fields surrounded by hedges and embankments) further inland.{{sfn|Trew|2004|pp=92, 132}} Roads led to the south via [[Asnelles]] and [[Ver-sur-Mer]].{{sfn|Trew|2004|p=34}} The terrain to the south-east rose to a ridge at [[Meuvaines]], where on D-day were located machine gun nests of the German 726th Regiment.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|pp=351–352}}
The [[Allied Expeditionary Air Force]] undertook over 3,200 photo reconnaissance sorties from April 1944 until the start of the invasion. Photos of the coastline were taken at extremely low altitude to show the invaders the terrain, obstacles on the beach, and defensive structures such as bunkers and gun emplacements. Inland terrain, bridges, troop emplacements, and buildings were also photographed, in many cases from several angles, to give the Allies as much information as possible.{{sfn|Zuehlke|2004|p=81}} Members of [[Combined Operations Pilotage Parties]] clandestinely prepared detailed harbour maps, including [[depth sounding]]s.{{sfn|Whitmarsh|2009|p=21}} At Gold, frogmen discovered the shore between Asnelles and La Rivière was soft and could not support the weight of tanks. Twelve [[Armoured Vehicle Royal Engineers]] (AVREs) were fitted with [[Hobart's Funnies#Designs|bobbin]]s to overcome this problem by deploying a roll of matting over the soft surface. The material would then be left in place to create a route for more conventional tanks.{{sfn|Trew|2004|p=41}}{{sfn|Wilmot|1997|p=195}}
[[File:The British Army in the United Kingdom 1939-45 H38264.jpg|thumb|British troops wade ashore during [[Exercise Fabius]], 6 May 1944. ]] Gold was assigned to the British [[XXX Corps (United Kingdom)|XXX Corps]], with the [[50th (Northumbrian) Infantry Division]] – commanded by Major General [[D.A.H. Graham]] – allotted as the assault division.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|p=271}} It was an experienced division that had already seen combat in France, North Africa, and Sicily.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|p=268}} The men underwent extensive training in amphibious landings, including [[Exercise Fabius]], a major training exercise at [[Hayling Island]] in May 1944.{{sfn|Yung|2006|p=153}} Demolition teams responsible for disabling underwater beach obstacles trained in swimming pools in the UK.{{sfn|Trew|2004|p=41}} Briefings were undertaken using detailed maps that used fictitious place names, and most of the men did not find out their destination until they were already on their way to Normandy.{{sfn|Whitmarsh|2009|pp=30, 36}} The amphibious landing was to be preceded by extensive air bombardment as well as naval bombardment by [[List of ships in Bombarding Force K|Bombarding Force K]], a task force of eighteen ships, primarily cruisers and destroyers.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|pp=271–272}}{{sfn|Trew|2004|p=49}} Amphibious tanks of the [[8th Armoured Brigade (United Kingdom)|8th Armoured Brigade]] were to arrive at 07:20, followed by infantry at 07:25.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|pp=276–277}} The 231st Brigade was assigned to land at Jig, and 69th Brigade at King. The 231st was to head west to capture Arromanches and establish contact with the American forces at Omaha, while the 69th was to move east and link up with the Canadian forces at Juno.{{sfn|Trew|2004|pp=34–35}} The 47th Royal Marine Commando was assigned to land at Gold, infiltrate inland, and capture the small port at Port-en-Bessin from the landward side.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|p=276}}
Arriving in the second wave on Jig, [[56th Infantry Brigade]] was to capture [[Bayeux]] and a nearby ridge, thus cutting the N13 highway between Caen and Bayeux to make it difficult for the Germans to move in reinforcements. The second wave on King, [[151st Infantry Brigade]], was tasked with capturing the Caen road and railway, along with setting up positions on high ground between the [[Aure (river)|Aure]] and Seulles rivers.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|p=278}}{{sfn|Trew|2004|pp=34, 38}} Other forces involved in the landing included artillery regiments, signals corps, and engineering units.{{sfn|Trew|2004|p=38}}
===German defences=== [[File:Batterie-longues-sur-mer.jpg|thumb|A gun emplacement at Longues-sur-Mer battery, photographed in 2008]] In late 1943, Hitler placed Field Marshal [[Erwin Rommel]] in charge of improving the coastal defences along the [[Atlantic Wall]] in anticipation of an Allied invasion, expected to take place sometime in 1944.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|p=30}} Rommel believed that the Normandy coast could be a possible landing point for the invasion, so he ordered the construction of extensive defensive works along that shore.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|p=54}} In the immediate area of Gold, between Le Hamel and La Rivière, seven defensive strongpoints designed to hold 50 men apiece were constructed. Two major concrete-reinforced coastal artillery emplacements (a battery of four 122&nbsp;mm guns at Mont Fleury and the [[Longues-sur-Mer battery]], with four 150&nbsp;mm guns) were only partially completed by D-Day.{{sfn|Trew|2004|pp=22–23}} Rommel ordered wooden stakes, metal tripods, mines, and large anti-tank obstacles to be placed on the beach to delay the approach of landing craft and impede the movement of tanks.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|pp=55–56}} Expecting the Allies to land at high tide so that the infantry would spend less time exposed on the beach, he ordered many of these obstacles to be placed at the high tide mark.{{sfn|Whitmarsh|2009|p=31}} Tangles of barbed wire, [[booby trap]]s, and the removal of ground cover made the approach hazardous for infantry.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|pp=54–56}}
Hitler gave Rommel command of the newly re-formed Army Group B, which included the [[7th Army (Wehrmacht)|7th Army]], the [[15th Army (Wehrmacht)|15th Army]], and the forces guarding the Netherlands. Reserves for this group included the [[116th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|2nd]], [[21st Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|21st]], and [[116th Panzer Division (Wehrmacht)|116th Panzer]] divisions.{{sfn|Goldstein|Dillon|Wenger|1994|p=12}}{{sfn|Whitmarsh|2009|p=12}} Recognizing that Allied air superiority would make it difficult if not impossible to move reserves into position once the invasion was underway, Rommel decided to concentrate the defences along the coast.{{sfn|Trew|2004|p=19}} The [[716th Static Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|716th Infantry Division]], which had been stationed in the area since March 1942, was significantly understrength, with only 6,000 men.{{sfn|Trew|2004|p=14}} This unit received reinforcements, and some of the older men were replaced by younger soldiers. It was also supplemented by several battalions of ''[[Osttruppen]]'' (eastern soldiers), conscripted Soviet prisoners of war.{{sfn|Trew|2004|pp=14, 18}} The [[352nd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|352nd Infantry Division]], a full-strength unit of around 12,000, was brought into the area by Rommel on 15 March and reinforced by two additional regiments.{{sfn|Ford|Zaloga|2009|pp=60, 63}} About 2,000 men, a mixture from the two infantry divisions, were stationed in the coastal area between Arromanches and Asnelles.{{sfn|Trew|2004|p=29}}
